			section
				figure
					img(src="/static/talk/heartbeat.png")
					figcaption
						small Click track is the heartbeat of the song

				aside.notes.
					What started life as the metronome, soon evolved into the electronic heart beat known as the ‘click track’, 
					a way of controlling other instruments so that they play in time with each other. 

					Through automation came synchronisation - keeping all instruments perfectly in time.

					As more parts of the music could be automated, fewer people were needed to make the music, so band sizes began to shrink, but more bands formed as a result, even solo artists were now a possibility!

			section
				figure
					//- img(src="/static/talk/MBO.png")
					video(data-autoplay, muted, src="/static/talk/graham-dunning-turntable-sequencer.mp4").full-size.wallpaper.monochromatic
			

					figcaption
						small Graham Dunning's		Turntable sequencer with mechanically geared rhythm patterns 
						
				aside.notes.
					Bands went from large orchestras with dozens of different instruments or choirs with hundreds of members, to smaller collectives assisted with technology.
						
			section
				figure
					video(data-autoplay, muted, src="/static/talk/graham-dunning-digital-turntable-sequencer.mp4").full-size.wallpaper.monochromatic

					figcaption
						small Graham Dunning's  Turntable sequencer with digital outputs

				aside.notes.
					So, machines revolutionised the process of making music as they not only had a fidelity and timing that most humans could only dream of, but they were reliable and very rarely made mistakes.

			section
				figure
					img(src="/static/talk/reel-to-reel.jpg")
					figcaption
						small Reel to Reel Audio Recording
						
				aside.notes.
					With the advent of recorded music, which was a way to make music once, but be able to listen to it forever.

					A single person, given time, could create music with many instruments by overlaying takes - superimposing layers of sounds over one another like a musical viennetta.

			section
