			section
				figure
					img(src="/static/talk/electronium.png")
					figcaption
						small Raymond Scott's Electronium
				aside.notes.
					The idea of offsetting a complicated and unforgiving process to a machine to handle on its own, is a liberating concept, and having a competent backing band at your command is certainly convenient. 

			section
				figure
					img(src="/static/talk/dx7.png")
					figcaption
						small Yamaha DX7 FM Synthesizer
				aside.notes.
					For many decades, Popular music was defined by the sounds of the tool that made the music. To replicate the distinct sound of 1980s music, use 1980s technologies.

					Everything would change forever however with the advent of digital signal processing, where every single nuance of a sound could be altered without a loss in quality. 

					Audio could now be manipulated at the atomic level.



			section
				
				aside.notes.

					TODO MELODYNE
										
					For example, automation could “correct” imperfections, such as altering a recording so that the singer was always in tune and in-time.

					At first these systems were slow and large but today they work in real time and on devices that fit into your smallest pocket. 

					The tools of today allow you to dynamically create or synthesize any sound or set of sounds without any musical background. 

					Automation, or automatic orchestration, meant perfect replication. 

					The click track automated tempo, digital interfaces like MIDI automated the melodies, then sampling came along and automated the timbres, the very sounds of the instruments themselves.

