			// --- Automation & Helping Technology -----------------
			section 
				aside.notes.
					For as long as there has been technological help, there have been people upset about it.
	
			//- Luddites
			section
				figure
					img(src="/static/talk/ned-ludd.png")
					figcaption
						small Ned Ludd, Leader of the Luddites

				aside.notes.
					In the early 1800s, nearby to Manchester -- birthplace of the industrial revolution, a group of disenfranchised textile workers, led by the enigmatic Ned Ludd, systematically destroyed the machinery that was brought in to increase productivity. 
					
					The looms and mills were vandelised beyond the point of repair. This pushback or, "collective bargaining", was powerful, but it was not the technology that the Luddites disagreed with, but how it required more demanding labour for the same pay. 
					
					The reduced price per product meant production had to exponentially increase. 

					They were not anti-technology or anti-progress, they just required fair compensation

			section
				figure
					img(src="/static/talk/calculator protest.jpg")
					figcaption
						small Calculator Protest

				aside.notes.
					In the late 20th century, electronic calculators became affordable and portable, leading to children bringing them into schools to help them with their maths, polarising teachers and parents... Was this cheating? 

					Anti-calculator protests kicked off.

					The teachers were not anti-technology or anti-progress, they just worried that essential skills would be replaced.
						

