					p.r-fit-text The robot, having no capacity for feeling, cannot produce music in a true sense.

				aside.notes.
					“The robot, having no capacity for feeling, cannot produce music in a true sense.”

					The campaign was unsuccessful, not because of the public outcry, but mainly because of economic factors such as the great depression that restricted theatre owners from hiring orchestras, leaving thousands of musicians out of work.

					They were not anti-technology or anti-progress, they just didn't want artistry to be automated.

			section
				figure
					img(src="/static/talk/MDL - A Profit without Honour.png")
					figcaption
						small Music Defense League - Profit Without Honour

				aside.notes.
					Rather than using recorded music, many theatres hired the one-man-band machine called the American Fotoplayer 

			section
				figure
					//- img(src="/static/talk/fotoplayer.png")
					img(src="/static/talk/fotoplayer.jpg")
					figcaption
						small American FotoPlayer
				aside.notes.
					Which replaced the band with a mostly automated orchestra, controlled using piano rolls, but operated by a real human employee, neatly sidestepping any controversy.

		


		
