				aside.notes.
					Everything is fine?



			section
				h3 Helpful Advice
				ol(role="list")
					li: p Always verify : Never believe anything a robot tells you
					li: p Don't expect them to have your best intentions at heart
					li: p Never let a robot write your references
					li: p Don't use it to write your papers, or your talks or to make lyrics or anything that represents you.
					li: p Making a pen that writes for you is not solving the correct problem
					li: p prompting into an LLM is not a safe space
					li: p Never trust a robot
					li: p Don't confuse language for meaning
					li: p Human mimicry should not be confused for sentience or consciousnous


			section
				h3 What have we learned?
				ol(role="list")
					li: p Musical instruments pre-date homosapians and were a gift from neanderthals  
					li: p Music can be entirely synthesized mathematically
					li: p Machine learning is great at figuring out patterns, trends and rules
					li: p Robots can be trained to deconstruct and reconstruct music
					li: p Music affects people in ways they cannot control
					li: p People are resilient to change and to the unfamiliar
					li: p Creativity is not unique to humans and is a skill that can be taught
					li: p Consciousness, like the human soul, probably doesn't exist

				aside.notes.
					Machines arguably will create the wildest jazz, the heaviest Industrial, the catchiest pop and, perhaps most surprising of all, the most punk punk. 
					
					A machine with no understanding of rhythm or tuning could theoretically even create a new Shaggs LP. 

					I am hopeful.


			section
				h3 Takeaways
				h4 Unanswered questions
				ol(role="list")
					li: p Will we ever consider robot art as good as “human art?
					li: p Do we need the Music Defense League to return? 
					li: p Were the Luddites right all along about labour?
					li: p What can we believe when everything can be faked?
					li: p At what point in automation can you still claim ownership?
					li: p If an A.I. creates anything, even in collaboration, who ultimately owns the copyright?
					li: p When information becomes ubiquitous does it become worthless?

				aside.notes.
					I’ll leave you with some things to think about for yourself

